=== RAW MODEL ANSWER ===
Answer: Step 1: Prepare the heteroaryl acyl donor by SNAr of the matching halonicotinic acid (the pyridyl acid corresponding to the fragment c4ccc(-n5cnnn5)nc4) with 1H-1,2,4-triazole to give the triazolyl‑nicotinic acid, then convert it to the acid chloride with SOCl2. | Step 2: Protect the piperidine N of 4-azaspiro[5.5]undecan-9-amine as Boc, acylate the exocyclic 9-amino group with that acid chloride to give Boc-protected 9-[(triazolyl‑nicotinoyl)amino]-4-azaspiro[5.5]undecane, then remove Boc to give the free piperidine NH amide intermediate. | Step 3: From 6-acetyl-7-methylphthalide (the methylphthalide fragment of the target), perform α-bromination of the acetyl group (Br2 or NBS) to obtain 6-(2-bromoacetyl)-7-methylphthalide. | Step 4: N-alkylate the free piperidine nitrogen of the spiro amide intermediate with 6-(2-bromoacetyl)-7-methylphthalide to form the connected amino ketone Ar-CO-CH2-N(azaspiro amide), where Ar is the 7-methylphthalide ring. | Step 5: Asymmetrically reduce that ketone (e.g., CBS/Noyori hydrogenation) to the required benzylic alcohol, setting the shown [C@@H] center and delivering Cc1c([C@@H](O)CN2CCC(C3(NC(=O)c4ccc(-n5cnnn5)nc4)CCC3)C2)ccc2c1COC2=O.

